The '''France national rugby union team''' is a national sporting side, representing [[France]] in [[rugby union]]. Rugby union is a popular sport in France, and the national team are one of the best in the world. France compete annually with [[England national rugby union team|England]], [[Italy national rugby union team|Italy]], [[Ireland national rugby union team|Ireland]], [[Scotland national rugby union team|Scotland]] and [[Wales national rugby union team|Wales]] in the [[Six Nations Championship]]. They have won the competition outright on 14 occasions, shared in another eight wins and completed eight [[Grand_Slam_%28Rugby_Union%29#Six_Nations_Championship|grand slams]]. They are the [[IRB World Rankings|second-ranked team]] in the world, behind only the [[All Blacks]].<ref name=WorldRank>{{cite web | publisher=irb.com|title=IRB World Rankings |url=http://www.irb.com/EN/World+Rankings/  |accessdate=2007-03-15}}</ref> France have competed at every [[Rugby World Cup]] and been runners-up twice. Six former French players have been inducted into the [[International Rugby Hall of Fame]].

Rugby was introduced to France in 1872 by the British and on [[New Year's Day]], [[1906]] the national side played its first [[Test match]] - against the All Blacks in Paris. France played irregularly against the [[Home Nations]] until they joined them to form a Five Nations tournament (today, the Six Nations) in 1910. France also competed in early [[Summer Olympics]] when rugby was included - winning one gold and two silver medals.

France came of age during the 1950s and 1960s, winning their first of many Five Nations. They won their first [[Grand Slam (rugby union)#Six Nations Championship|Grand Slam]] in 1968, and won numerous titles in the following years. Since the inaugural World Cup in 1987, France qualified for the  knock out stage of every tournament, and were runners-up to the All Blacks in [[1987 Rugby World Cup|1987]] and to [[Australia national rugby union team|Australia]] in [[1999 Rugby World Cup|1999]].

France traditionally play in [[blue]] shirts with [[white]] shorts and [[red]] socks, and are commonly referred to as the ''les tricolors'' or ''les bleus''. The French emblem is a red badge with a [[rooster]]. Their alternative strip is mainly white. French internationals are played at a variety of venues throughout the country, but it is [[Stade de France]] in the [[Paris]] suburb of [[Saint-Denis]] that is used for their games during the Six Nations. France are the host nation of the upcoming [[2007 Rugby World Cup]].

==History==
{{main|History of the French national rugby union team}}
Rugby was introduced to France in 1872 by British merchants and students in the 1870s.<ref name="hundyears">{{cite web | url=http://www.irb.com/EN/News/Features/061114+dk+fre+rugby+100.htm| title=100 years of French Test rugby: part one | publisher=International Rugby Board | author=Chris Thau | date= [[2006-11-14]]| accessdate=2007-03-29}}</ref> Although France were represented at the [[1900 Summer Olympics]] (where they won gold),<ref name="olympics">{{cite web | url=http://www.rugbyfootballhistory.com/olympics.htm#france1900| title=Rugby at the 1924 Olympics | publisher=Rugby Football History | accessdate=2007-03-04}}</ref> their first official Test match did not take place till [[New Year's Day]], [[1906]] against the [[All Blacks]] in [[Paris]].<ref name="ABGame88">{{cite web| url=http://stats.allblacks.com/teamsheet.asp?MT_ID=1088 |title=8th All Black Test : 88th All Black Game |publisher=allblacks.com |accessdate=2007-03-30}}</ref> France then played irregularly against the [[Home Nations]] until they joined them to form the Five Nations tournament (since expanded to the Six Nations Championship) in 1910. In 1913 France faced [[South African]]'s [[South Africa national rugby union team|Springboks]] for the first time; losing 38-5.<ref name="SAvsFraP3">{{cite web| url=http://www.rugbydata.com/southafrica/france/gamesplayed/3 |title=South Africa vs France > Games Played |publisher=rugbydata.com |accessdate=2007-05-17}}</ref> France also competed at the [[1920 Summer Olympics|1920]] and [[1924 Summer Olympics|1924]] Summer Olympics and on both occasions lost infamously to the [[United States national rugby union team|United States]] in the gold medal match.<ref name="olympics"/>

Having achieved their first victories against the [[England national rugby union team|English]] and [[Wales national rugby union team|Welsh]] in the late 1920s, they were ejected from the Five Nations in 1932.<ref name="fivenations">{{cite web | url=http://www.rugbyworld.com/Story/0,18830,3551_1884973,00.html| title=2/3/4/5/6 Nations Winners | publisher=Rugby World | accessdate=2007-03-04}}</ref> This was mainly due to accusations of professionalism in the French leagues.<ref name="fivenations"/>
<ref name="nationshistory">{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/international/1776391.stm |title=Six Nations history |publisher=BBC Sport date=28 January, 2002 |accessdate=2007-04-02}}</ref> Despite not playing the Home Nations, France created a winning streak which still stands today.<ref name="WinningStreak">{{cite web| url=http://www.rugbydata.com/france/mostwinsinarow |title=France > Most Wins in a row |publisher=rugbydata.com |accessdate=2007-05-17}}</ref> France would not rejoin until 1939 when they were invited back, though international rugby was suspended during the war.<ref name="nationshistory"/>

France came of age during the 1950s and 1960s - winning their first of many Five Nations as well as completing a successful tour of South Africa.<ref name="nationshistory"/> Their first championship was won in 1954 when they shared the title with England and Wales.<ref name="results">{{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/international/4629242.stm| title=Six Nations roll of honour | publisher=BBC Sport | accessdate=2007-04-02}}</ref><ref name="nationshistory"/> France became the first nation from the [[northern hemisphere]] to tour South Africa - rocking the Springboks to win the Test series. In 1959 France won their first out-right Five Nations championship.<ref name="results"/> The Springboks also visited Paris, though the Test was not completed due to fighting. France also toured [[New Zealand]] and [[Australia]] - losing both Tests against the All Blacks but defeating Australia's [[Australia national rugby union team|Wallabies]]. They won their first [[Grand Slam (rugby union)#Six Nations Championship|Grand Slam]] in 1968, and won numerous titles in the following years.<ref name="results"/>
[[Image:France-Wales 24022007 - 10.jpg|thumb|250px|left|France playing Wales during the [[Six Nations Championship]].]]
The 1970s were also a successful for France, and in 1977 they won their second Grand Slam, fielding an unchanged side throughout the tournament.<ref name="results"/> They also defeated the All Blacks in [[Toulouse]] that year, though they lost the return match in Paris.<ref name="tourfra">{{cite web| url=http://stats.allblacks.com/tourbreak.asp?IDID=77 |title=1977 in France |publisher=allblacks.com |accessdate=2007-04-02}}</ref> They also defeated the All Blacks in New Zealand for the first time on [[Bastille Day]], [[1979]] at [[Eden Park]].<ref name="ABGame79">{{cite web| url=http://stats.allblacks.com/teamsheet.asp?level1=All_Blacks&Level2=ABC&MT_ID=1753 |title=184th All Black Test : 753rd All Black Game |publisher=allblacks.com |accessdate=2007-04-02}}</ref> The 1980s saw another successful era for the French - who clinched their third Grand Slam at [[Twickenham Stadium|Twickenham]] against the English in 1981.<ref name="results"/> France completed a Grand Slam in 1987 on the eve of the first [[Rugby World Cup]] hosted by Australia and New Zealand. They came from behind numerous times to defeat the Wallabies in their semi-final, and faced the All Blacks in final at Eden Park, [[Auckland]]; France lost 29 points to 9. They shared the Five Nations with Wales the next year, and also won it in 1989.<ref name="results"/>

France - who hosting some games - made their exit from the [[1991 Rugby World Cup|1991 World Cup]] after being knocked out by England at Twickenham in their quarter-final. One Five Nations championship was won in the early 1990s; in 1993. The following year France won a Test series 2-0 in New Zealand.<ref name="tour1">{{cite web| url=http://stats.allblacks.com/tourbreak.asp?IDID=126 |title=1994 France in New Zealand |publisher=allblacks.com |accessdate=2007-04-02}}</ref> They were knocked out of the [[1995 Rugby World Cup|1995 World Cup]] semi-finals by eventual champions the Springboks, but did win their third place play-off match against England. France won back-to-back Grand Slams in 1997 and 1998 and  performed strongly at the [[1999 Rugby World Cup|1999 World Cup]].<ref name="results"/> They defeated tournament favourites the All Blacks in the semi-finals, but lost to the Wallabies in the final.

In the expanded Six Nations Championship (now including Italy) France won a Grand Slam in 2002.<ref name="results"/> At the [[2003 Rugby World Cup|2003 World Cup]] in Australia they got as far as the semi-finals, where they were defeated by eventual champions England. In 2004 they won a second Grand Slam under the new championship format. This was followed by a win in 2006 and successful title defence in 2007.<ref name="results"/>

==Strip==
[[Image:Logo XV de france.JPG|250px|thumb|A uniform of the French rugby team, with the traditional rooster symbol.]]
Until 1912, the uniform of the French team was not blue and did not have a rooster on it, but was white with two rings, one red and one blue. The rings were chosen by France  as its symbol for the Olympic games, there were only two rings because only two continents, America and Europe, participated in the Olympic games at that time.<ref name="logo1">{{fr icon}}{{cite web | url=http://www.sncf.com/actu/rugby/LSDT-premier-maillot-Equipe-France.html| title=Le premier maillot de l'Equipe de France | publisher=Sncf.com | accessdate=2007-03-04}}</ref>

After the first game won by France, against Scotland in 1911, Marcel Communeau who was then captain of the French team, asked that the team adopt the ''coq'' (rooster) as its symbol.<ref name="logo2">{{fr icon}}{{cite web | url=http://rugby-nomades.qc.ca/info-nomades/histoire_1911.php| title=2 janvier 1911 : la naissance d’une Nation | publisher=Rugby-nomades.qc.ca | accessdate=2007-03-04}}</ref> The rooster was probably chosen because it is considered as a proud and combative animal, that can be sometimes aggressive. The rooster was used previously as a symbol by a French team, a former soccer player, Jean Rigal, wore a uniform with this emblem as early as May 1910.<ref name="logo3">{{fr icon}}{{cite web | url=http://crdp.ac-bordeaux.fr/rugby/arts/5-01-02.pdf| title=Le coq dans le sport  | publisher=Crdp.ac-bordeaux.fr | accessdate=2007-03-04}}</ref>

The badge was initially white and red, then was embroidered and multicoloured after 1945, and golden since 1970.<ref name="logo4">{{fr icon}}{{cite web | url=http://crdp.ac-bordeaux.fr/rugby/arts/5-01-01.pdf| title=Le coq sportif | publisher=Crdp.ac-bordeaux.fr | accessdate=2007-03-04}}</ref> The representation of the rooster was first realistic and detailed, later the outline was simplified; it is now abstract and stylized.

The symbol used by the French rugby team was a great success, and was later adopted by the French delegation at the Olympic games of 1920 where the rooster is perched on five Olympic rings.<ref name="logo5">{{fr icon}}{{cite web | url=http://www.museedusport.fr/histoire_objet.php| title=Ecusson en forme de coq, devenu emblème national | publisher=Musee du Sport | accessdate=2007-03-04}}</ref> The rooster is a well known symbol of French teams. French players are sometimes called ''les coqs'' and some French supporters used to release a rooster on the playing field before a game.

The French team traditionally played in Blue shirts, whites shorts, and red socks, and as such they were nicknamed ''les tricolores''. Due to the mostly blue [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] strip the French team currently plays in, the team being is often referred to as ''les Bleus'' (The Blue). When necessary (home games against Scotland and Italy), French players wear white colours. The reason for the home side changing strip is due to the rugby tradition of the home side changing strips in the event of a colour clash. New strips have been developed for the 2007 World Cup - one which is a darker blue - which would likely see the All Blacks wear grey if they were to meet in the tournament.<ref name="new">{{fr icon}}{{cite web | url=http://home.nzcity.co.nz/news/default.aspx?id=72647&cat=977| title=All Blacks may not be all black | publisher=NZ City | accessdate=2007-05-01}}</ref> It was rumoured to be a move to gain a psychological edge over the All Blacks, but this was dismissed.<ref name="new"/>

==Home grounds==
[[Image:France All Blacks 16-11-2002.jpg|thumb|250px|left|France hosting the All Blacks at the Stade de France.]]
France plays internationals at a number of grounds throughout the country. Home matches during the Six Nations are played at [[Stade de France]], [[Saint Denis]] ([[Paris]]).<ref name=sixnationsvenues>{{cite web | publisher=rbs6nations.com | title=Stade de France|url=http://www.rbs6nations.com/stadium_france.htm|accessdate=2007-04-02}}</ref> During the 2005 and 2006 seasons, France also played home internationals at venues such as [[Stade Gerland]], [[Lyon]]; [[Stade Vélodrome]], [[Marseille]]; [[Stade de la Beaujoire]], [[Nantes]] and [[Stadium Municipal|Stadium de Toulouse]], [[Toulouse]].<ref>An archive of international results can be found at [http://www.irb.com/EN/Fixtures+and+Results/ www.irb.com] accessed [[2007-05-06]]</ref>

At the [[2007 Rugby World Cup]], there are ten venues being used for matches throughout the country (Cardiff, Wales and Edinburgh, Scotland will also host some games).<ref name=wcvenues>{{cite web | publisher=rugbyworldcup.com | title=Destination France|url=http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/EN/Destination+France/|accessdate=2007-04-02}}</ref> The French cities hosting matches at the World Cup are [[Stade Félix Bollaert]], [[Lens, Pas-de-Calais|Lens]]; Stade de France, Saint-Denis; [[Parc des Princes]], [[Paris]]; Stade de la Beaujoire, Nantes; [[Stade Chaban-Delmas]], [[Bordeaux]], Stade Gerland, Lyon; [[Stade Geoffroy-Guichard]], [[Saint-Étienne]], [[Stade de la Mosson]], [[Montpellier]]; Stadium de Toulouse, Toulouse and Stade Vélodrome, Marseille.<ref name="wcvenues"/> The final of the World Cup will be played at Stade de France.

Though 2007 is the first Rugby World Cup hosted by France, there have been multiple games played in France earlier during the [[1991 Rugby World Cup|1991]] and [[1999 Rugby World Cup|1999]] tournaments (primarily hosted by England and Wales respectively). In 1991, all Pool D matches (France's pool) were held around France, along with two quarter finals (England v France at Parc des Princes and New Zealand v Canada at [[Stadium Lille-Metropole]]).<ref name="1991RWCVenues">{{cite web| url=http://www.worldcupweb.com/WCrugby/1991.asp |publisher=worldcupweb.com |accessdate=2007-05-06 |title=1991 Rugby World Cup Results}}</ref> In 1999, similar to 1991, all Pool C (France's pool) matches were held around France along with one second round play-off and quarter final (at Stade de France).<ref name="1999RWCvenues">{{cite web| url=http://www.worldcupweb.com/WCrugby/1999.asp |title=1999 Rugby World Cup Results |publisher=worldcupweb.com |accessdate=2007-05-06}}</ref>

During the early years France played internationals at venues such as Parc des Princes in Paris and the [[Stade Olympique Yves-du-Manoir|Stade Olympique de Colombes]] (also in Paris).<ref name=parc>{{cite web | publisher=2rugby.com | title=Parc des Princes|url=http://2rugby.com/ground/26/|accessdate=2007-04-02}}</ref><ref name=colom>{{cite web | publisher=2rugby.com | title=Stade Colombes|url=http://2rugby.com/ground/27/|accessdate=2007-04-02}}</ref> The Stade Olympique de Colombes, or the Stade Olympique Yves-du-Manoir, was the main venue at the [[1924 Summer Olympics]], where rugby was also a sport.<ref name="olympics"/> The largest stadium that France currently plays at is the Stade de France, which is where the [[Top 14]] final is also held - it has a capacity of 80,000.<ref name=sixnationsvenues/>

==Record==
===Six Nations===
Frances' only annual tournament is the [[Six Nations Championship]], which is played against five other European Nations; England, Ireland, Italy, Scotland and Wales. France first contested the tournament in 1910 when the Home Nations became the Five Nations (Italy would later join in 2000).<ref name="RollofHonour">{{cite web| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/international/3422419.stm |title=Six Nations roll of honour |publisher=bbc.co.uk |accessdate=2007-05-03 |date=[[2004-01-29]]}}</ref> Not playing during the 1932–1939 seasons, they would join again in 1947. They first won in 1954, sharing the championship with both England and Wales. France shared with Wales again the next season, but won it alone for the first time in 1959.<ref name="RollofHonour"/> France's longest wait for a championship spanned 37 tournaments (1910 to 1954).

{{Six Nations wins}}

===World Cup===
Although France have competed at every [[Rugby World Cup]] since the inaugural tournament in 1987, they have never won the competition.<ref name="RWCRecord">{{Citation |title=France |magazine=Rugby News |year=2007 |volume=38 |issue=9 |page=50}}</ref> They have however played in the quarter final stages of every tournament, and made the final twice. In 1987 they were defeated by the All Blacks 29-9 at [[Eden Park]] in the final.<ref name=1987Final>{{cite web | publisher=allblacks.com | title=231st All Black Test : 871st All Black Game | url=http://stats.allblacks.com/teamsheet.asp?MT_ID=1871 |accessdate=2007-05-03}}</ref> They were knocked out by England in the quarter-finals of the 1991 competition - their worst ever finish. In 1995 France finished third overall, defeating England 19-9 in the third/fourth place play-off after their defeat to South Africa in their semi-final. After coming from behind to defeating the All Blacks in their 1999 semi-final,<ref name=1999Semi>{{cite web | publisher=allblacks.com | title=335th All Black Test : 1053rd All Black Game | url=http://stats.allblacks.com/teamsheet.asp?MT_ID=2053  |accessdate=2007-05-03}}</ref> France lost to Australia in the final. In 2003 they finished fourth; losing the third/fourth place game to the All Blacks.<ref name=2003Fourth>{{cite web | publisher=allblacks.com | title=381st All Black Test : 1101st All Black Game | url=http://stats.allblacks.com/teamsheet.asp?MT_ID=2101  |accessdate=2007-05-03}}</ref>

France are the third highest Rugby World Cup points scorers of all time (968 points); the third highest  try scorers , and the third highest penalty scorers.<ref name=RWCPoints>{{cite web| url=http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/EN/RWC+Statistics/RWC+Team+Stats/ |title=Team Statistics (Displaying top 20 with ties) |publisher=rugbyworldcup.com |accessdate=2007-05-02}}</ref> Frenchman [[Thierry Lacroix]] was the highest points scorer at the 1995 tournament (112 points), and [[Jean-Baptiste Lafond]] the joint top try scorer in 1991 (6 tries; equal with [[David Campese]]).<ref name=RWCPlayers>{{cite web| url=http://www.rugbyworldcup.com/EN/RWC+Statistics/RWC+Player+Stats/ |title=Player Statistics (Displaying top 20 with ties) |publisher=rugbyworldcup.com |accessdate=2007-05-02}}</ref>

===Overall===
France have won 347 of their 623 matches played, a win record of 55.70%.<ref name="RugbyDataOverall">{{cite web| url=http://www.rugbydata.com/france/teamsplayed |title=International Teams > France > Teams Played |publisher=rugbydata.com |accessdate=2007-03-29 |date=[[2007-03-17]]}}</ref><ref>Statistics exclude the match played against [[New Zealand Māori rugby union team|New Zealand Māori]] as this is not a full international side.</ref> When the [[IRB World Rankings|World Rankings]] were introduced by the IRB in 2003 France were ranked fifth. During November 2003 France briefly occupied third before falling to fourth by December that year. After falling to fifth during November 2004, France rose again to fourth by April 2005. After rising to third in the rankings in April 2006, France rose to second in July that year. France has been ranked number two in the world since then.<ref name="RankingsArchive">Ranking archives can be found at the IRB website; [http://www.irb.com www.irb.com]</ref>

Their Test match record against all nations, updated to [[29 March]] 2007, is as follows:<ref name="RugbyDataOverall"/>

