===Individual records===
The record for points scored for France is 380 held by Christophe Lamaison.<ref name="Records">{{cite web| url=http://www.ffr.fr/index.php/ffr/equipes_de_france/xv_de_france/records | title=Records | publisher=ffr.fr |accessdate=2007-04-10 |language=French}}</ref> Lamaison also holds the record for conversions with 60.<ref name="Records"/> The record for penalties scored is 89 by Thierry Lacroix, and the drop goal record is held by Jean-Patrick Lescarboura.<ref name="Records"/> The record for French appearances is held by Philipe Sella with 111 appearances; he also holds the record for Test appearances with 38.<ref name="Records"/>

==Training and selection==
===Coaches===
Historically the role of French rugby coach (or ''trainer'') has varied significantly. Due to the status of rugby union as an amateur sport for most of it's history, the job of deciding tactics and running team trainings has often been that of the captain or senior players. Therefore a comprehensive list of national coaches is impossible. 

Although coached by [[Jean Desclaux]] between 1973 and 1980, the French team's main influence during the late 1970 was captain [[Jacques Fouroux]]. Fouroux played {{scrum-half}} and captained France to their 1977 Five Nations Grand Slam where France played a very forward oriented style of rugby.<ref name="Dine155">Dine (2001), pg 155.</ref> Although the style of ''Fouroux's Gang'' was successful it was criticised because it contrasted with the traditional open attacking style of French rugby.<ref name="Dine155"/> Fouroux was given the nickname "the little Corporal" - the same as [[Napolean Bonaparte]].<ref name="FourouxTelObituary">{{cite web| url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2005/12/20/db2002.xml |title=Jacques Fouroux |publisher=telegraph.co.uk |date=[[2005-12-20]] |accessdate=2007-05-06}}</ref> Fouroux was named as Cazenave's successor in 1981 at the age of just 33. He continued to promote a forward oriented style of play and France won six Five Nations titles, including two Grand Slams while he was coach. After nearly ten years as French coach he resigned in 1990 after a defeat to Romania.<ref name="Dine160">Dine (2001), pg 160.</ref>

Fouroux was succeeded by [[Daniel Dubroca]] who coached the team to the 1991 Rugby World Cup.<ref name="Brine172">Brine (2001), pg 172-173.</ref> Dubroca's tenure as coach did not last long however as he resigned after violently confronting referee [[David Bishop]] following France's World Cup quarter-final against England.<ref name="Brine172"/><ref name="1992IHT">{{cite news| url=http://www.iht.com/articles/1992/03/19/rugb.php |title=French, in Anglo-Saxon Game, Can No Longer Rest on Latin Laurels |publisher=International Herald Tribune |accessdate=2007-05-06 |date=[[1992-03-19]] |last=Patel |first=Tara}}</ref> Dubroca was replaced by [[Pierre Berbizier]] who coached the team until after the 1995 Rugby World Cup.<ref name="BerbizierAttack">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/rugby_union/6311205.stm |title=Berbizier launches Laporte attack |publisher=bbc.co.uk |accessdate=2007-05-06 |date=[[2007-01-29]]}}</ref> Berbizier's replacement [[Jean-Claude Skrela]] coached France to Five Nations Grand Slams in 1997 and 1998 before they got the wooden spoon in 1999.<ref name="SkrelaQuit">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/sport/rugby_union/523219.stm |title=Sport: Rugby Union Skrela steps down as French coach |publisher=bbc.co.uk |accessdate=2007-05-06 |date=[[1999-11-16]]}}</ref> He told the FFR he would step down prior to the 1999 Rugby World Cup, and officially resigned following France's loss to Australia in the tournament final. [[Bernard Laporte]] was appointed as Skrela's successor in November 1999 and has held the position ever since.<ref name="LaporteAppointed">{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/sport/rugby_union/532229.stm |title=Laporte gets France job |publisher=bbc.co.uk |accessdate=2007-05-06 |date=[[1999-11-22]]}}</ref>

