===National Rugby Centre===
[[Image:Centre rugby linas marcoussis.jpg|thumb|350px|right|Frances' National Rugby Centre located in Marcoussis.]]
The National Rugby Centre (NRC) was opened by then French President [[Jacques Chirac]] in November 2002.<ref name="NRCOpening">{{cite news| title=All Blacks are not dangerous, says French coach |publisher=Reuters News |first=Jean-Paul |last=Couret |date=[[2002-11-19]]}}</ref> The facility cost £46 million, and is located in  the village of Marcoussis, south of [[Paris]].<ref name="46mNRC">{{cite news| url=http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2003/05/26/story781523988.asp |title=Bord Bia launch lamb promotion |publisher=Irish Examiner |accessdate=2007-05-06 |date=[[2003-05-26]] |last=Ryan |first=Ray}}</ref><ref name="NRCOpening"/> The facility covers 20 hectares and includes five rugby pitches (one of them covered, and two floodlit), a gym, medical facilities, a swimming pool, media centre, and library.<ref name="NRCFacilities">{{cite news| title=French players enjoy new home |publisher=Reuters News |date=[[2002-11-08]] |first=Jean-Paul |last=Couret}}</ref> Living quarters are also included, and totals 30 rooms that are each named after a championship winning French club. The living quarters also has a dedicated restaurant. France's under 19 team permanently live at the NRC, and can provide opposition for the French team during training.<ref name="NRCFacilities"/>

